at-grandparents. At the same time, using sophisticated molecular methods, scientists are upending conventional wisdom about the role of microbes in every part of the world. Their research reveals the resilience and complexity of the indigenous microbial communities that contribute to the flavor and safety of cheese. One experiment at a time, these dynamic scientists, cheesemakers, and dairy farmers are reinventing the wheel.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCheese industry. 0aCheesexMicrobiology. 0aCheesemakers. 0aCheesemakingxTechnological innovations. 0aCheesemaking. 0aDairy farmingxTechnological innovations. 0aRaw milkxMicrobiology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Agriculture & Food (see also POLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Agriculture & Food Policy).2bisacsh1 aPercival, Francis, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311066755440uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096446440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520964464423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520964464/original  a978-3-11-066755-4  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles